        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἄστυλλος" type="patronymic">Ἀστύλλ<supplied reason="lost">ω</supplied></name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#-ύστρατος" type="patronymic"><gap reason="lost" atLeast="1" atMost="3" unit="character"/><seg part="F"><unclear>υ</unclear>στράτ<unclear>ω</unclear></seg></name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#-είδας" type="patronymic"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><seg part="F">είδα</seg></name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="4"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἁνίοχος" type="patronymic"><supplied reason="lost">Ἁ</supplied>νιόχ<unclear>ω</unclear></name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="5"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name> <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ἀνδρόνικος" type="patronymic"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀνδ</supplied><unclear>ρ</unclear>ονί<unclear>κ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ω</supplied></name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="5a"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"/>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="2" type="alternative">
                    <lem><gap reason="lost" atLeast="1" atMost="3" unit="character"/><unclear>υ</unclear>στράτ<unclear>ω</unclear></lem>
                    <rdg><supplied reason="lost">Ε</supplied><unclear>ὐ</unclear>στράτ<unclear>ω</unclear> or <supplied reason="lost">Λεβ</supplied><unclear>υ</unclear>στράτ<unclear>ω</unclear></rdg>
                </app></p>
                
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Un tel</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">fils d'</supplied>Astyllos, <supplied reason="lost">Un tel</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">fils de</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>ystratos, <supplied reason="lost">Un tel</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">fils de</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>eidas, <supplied reason="lost">Un tel</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">fils d'</supplied>Haniokhos, <supplied reason="lost">Un tel</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">fils d'</supplied>Andronikos, <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">So and so</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">son of</supplied> Astyllos, <supplied reason="lost">So and so</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">son of</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>ystratos, <supplied reason="lost">So and so</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">son of</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>eidas, <supplied reason="lost">So and so</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">son of</supplied> Haniochos, <supplied reason="lost">So and so</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">son of</supplied> Andronikos, <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Il tale</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">figlio di</supplied> Astyllos, <supplied reason="lost">Il tale</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">figlio di</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>ystratos, <supplied reason="lost">Il tale</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">figlio di</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>eidas, <supplied reason="lost">Il tale</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">figlio di</supplied> Haniochos, <supplied reason="lost">Il tale</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">figlio di</supplied> Andronikos, <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>This very carefully cut inscription lists names at the genitive case, thus fathers' names. Amongst them, Haniochos is very common and typical of Cyrenaica. Astyllos is already 
                 attested only once (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr065200</ref> a.i.54), with a lost father's name, at the beginning of the same century. For the name at line 2, amongst the possible restorations, three are favourite: <foreign xml:lang="grc">Εὔστρατος</foreign>, which is the name of a military 
                 officer about 335 BC (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr084000</ref> b.1.88); <foreign xml:lang="grc">Πολύστρατος</foreign>, of which the short form <foreign xml:lang="grc">Πόλυστρις</foreign> is a priest's name in <ref
                      type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr115000</ref> i.36, in the second half of the third century BC; or <foreign xml:lang="grc">Λι/εβύστρατος</foreign>, a local name attested on coins and also attested twice in a lost context dated into the fourth century BC (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr080300</ref> a.2 and 
                 <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr097100</ref> a.27). As for Andronikos, it is attested only once at the end of the second century BC (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr115000</ref> ii.25). We can only conclude that the men listed here belonged to the upper class of the Hellenistic Cyrene.</p>
            </div></body>
